RubyDome

Target IP: 192.168.156.22
Challenge Description: N/A

Reconnaissance


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.


Doing an aggressive port scan against the two open TCP ports returns the result above. The TCP application on port 3000 seems to be HTTP. I will start enumeration with this application.


Performing a whatweb scan shows the technology above used by the target machine.

Enumeration

Port 3000: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. This application seems to be making a POST request to /pdf according to the source-code of this webpage.


I sent the URL http://192.168.156.22:3000/pdf as the input and obtained the useful error message above. The target machine seems to be using pdfkit which uses Ruby. I tried to use the application to generate a valid PDF to identify the application version, but I had no luck.


Doing a Google search for PDFKit exploits shows it is vulnerable to command injection, as shown above. This has the CVE of CVE-2022-25765. I found an exploit with the name 51293.py using searchsploit.

Exploitation


I came across the PoC above at this Github repository. I followed the instructions above on my machine and made the request using curl.


In the image above, there are three terminals. The terminal on top is used for the Python HTTP server. The middle terminal is where I deploy the curl payload. And the terminal on bottom is where I obtain the reverse shell connection with the session as andrew. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Running sudo -l shows the interesting entry above. This user can execute the command /usr/bin/ruby /home/andrew/app/app.rb. Since this application is inside the home directory of user andrew, I can modify this file.


On my machine, I created the Ruby reverse shell script with the name app.rb as shown above. I found this reverse shell script here. Then I transferred this file to the target machine.


Then I started a listener on my machine at port 8444. And I executed the command sudo /usr/bin/ruby /home/andrew/app/app.rb. Now I have a root shell, as shown above :)
